'''Richard Restak''' (born 1942) is an [[United States|American]] [[neurologist]], [[neuropsychiatrist]], [[author]] and  [[professor]].

== Education ==
Restak is a [[graduation|graduate]] of [[Gettysburg College]] and [[Georgetown University School of Medicine]]. He performed his [[postgraduate]] training in [[New York City]] at [[Saint Vincent's Catholic Medical Center|St. Vincent's Hospital]] ([[Manhattan]]) where he completed his [[internship]]. His first psychiatric [[residency (medicine)|residency]] was also in New York City at [[Mount Sinai Hospital, New York|Mount Sinai Hospital]]. This was followed by two residencies in Washington,D.C.. A psychiatric residency at [[Georgetown University Hospital]], and a residency in neurology at [[George Washington]] [[University]] [[Hospital]].<ref>[http://www.psychiatrictimes.com/p950927.html Psychiatric Times]</ref>

== Career ==
Restak maintains a private [[medical practice]] in neurology and neuropsychiatry in Washington, D.C. where he is also a  Clinical [[Professor]] of Neurology at George Washington Hospital University School of [[Medicine]] and [[Health]]. 

He has to date written 18 books on various aspects of the human brain, two were on The New York Times Best Sellers List. His first bestseller, ''The Brain'' (1984), was also the first companion book he wrote for a PBS series.  ''The Mind'' (1988), was his second bestseller.He has written articles for various national newspapers as well as appearing on [[radio]] and [[television]] programs.<ref>[http://discuss.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/zforum/02/tv_pbs021302.htm Transcript, The Secret Life of the Brain, With Dr. Richard Restak], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Feb. 13, 2002</ref><ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/books/97/06/22/reviews/970622.22restakt.html New York Times]</ref><ref>[http://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/199203/armchair-shell-shock Armchair Shell Shock], ''[[Psychology Today]]'', March 1, 1992</ref> 

He has appeared as an [[expert witness]] for the defense in the high profile trial of [[Mir Aimal Kasi]]. The [[Pakistani people|Pakistani]] national charged with the 1993 shootings at [[CIA]] headquarters in [[Langley, Virginia]]. During the trial Restak testified that Kasi was missing tissue from his [[frontal lobes]]. A [[congenital]] defect that affected his ability to judge the consequences of his actions.<ref>[http://www.dana.org/news/cerebrum/detail.aspx?id=3356 Dana Foundation]</ref><ref>[http://cgi.cnn.com/US/9711/12/cia.shooting.trial/index.html CNN]</ref>

